    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing leaves with green veins, a classic sign, is often a symptom of nutrient issues, but it could be a few things. It's a bit tricky to tell if it's nitrogen deficiency or a pH imbalance without more info, but I'd suggest starting with a soil test. A soil test will tell you exactly what nutrients your bushes are lacking and what your pH level is, which is the most direct way to figure out what's going on. You can usually get these through your local agricultural extension office.\n\nIt's much better to test first than to just start dumping amendments on your bushes, which could cause more problems. Once you know your soil's condition, you can address the specific deficiency, whether it's a nutrient or a pH adjustment. Keep in mind that some nutrient deficiencies look similar, so a test is your best friend here.\n\nThis is a good starting point for troubleshooting, and you can tackle it methodically. Good luck with your bushes!\n\n*Self-Correction/Refinement: I need to ensure I am not just giving advice, but also framing it in a way that suggests a low-effort, high-impact action, which is the soil test.*\n\n(Wait",
